State MSM Profile: Pennsylvania

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Pennsylvania

An estimated 162,744 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Pennsylvania in 2013, representing 3.6% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 4,798,340 adult men of Pennsylvania, 3.4% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Pennsylvania resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (37.0%). Including both central and fringe counties, 69.6% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Pennsylvania, 2013

MSM in Pennsylvania Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Pennsylvania, Philadelphia County had the largest population of MSM at 33,549, representing 20.6% of all MSM in the state. Pike County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Pennsylvania at 7.2%. This was greater than the percentage for Pennsylvania as a whole, which was 3.4% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Pennsylvania Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington MSA overlaps four states: Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey and Pennsylvania. The Pennsylvania portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Pennsylvania at 72,394, or 44.5% of all MSM in the state and 72.2% of the 100,293 MSM in the MSA. Of the 1,469,540 adult men in the Pennsylvania part of Philadelphia-Camden-Wilmington, an estimated 4.9% were MSM. This was greater than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 4.6% of adult men (100,293 out of 2,189,761).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.

Of 267,440 adult men in the Pennsylvania part of Allentown-Bethlehem-Easton, 2.2% were MSM. This was greater than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 2.1% of adult men (6,577 out of 307,373).
